Taiwan Dollar Erases Weekly Gain on Suspected Intervention

-- B y   A n d r e a   W o n g
-- 
2011-05-13T08:54:59Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-05-13/taiwan-dollar-gains-on-optimism-economic-growth-to-lure-funds.html
Taiwan ’s dollar erased a weekly gain
in the final minutes of trading on suspected intervention by the
central bank, according to two traders who refused to be
identified as the authority doesn’t disclose such details.  The currency rose as much as 1.1 percent this week to reach
a 13-year high after official data showed exports climbed 24.6
percent from a year earlier in April to a record $27.3 billion.
The Taiwan dollar has appreciated 5.5 percent this year, the
best performance among  Asia ’s 10 most-traded currencies, as
global funds bought some $3 billion more Taiwanese stocks than
they sold during the period, according to exchange data.  “The Taiwan dollar’s appreciation has attracted foreign
investors to Taiwanese assets,” said Ivy Leung, a Taipei-based
fixed income trader at Polaris Securities Co. “They have been
buying corporate debt and short-dated  government bonds 
recently.”  The currency closed at NT$28.788 against the greenback,
less than 0.05 percent away from its levels yesterday and a week
ago, according to Taipei Forex Inc. It touched NT$28.476 on May
11, the strongest level since October 1997. The  Taiwan dollar 
was 0.4 percent stronger three minutes before the end of today’s
trading session.  Government bonds fell this week. The yield on the 1 percent
note due January 2016, the most-traded government debt, gained
one basis point to 1.102 percent, according to Gretai Securities
Market. A basis point is 0.01 percentage point.  To contact the reporters on this story:
